    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-02-01T00:29:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-02-01T00:29:00-05:00" n="433"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d433">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 837.00/1059</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Minister <persName type="from">Gonzales</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Habana</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-02-01T00:00:00-05:29">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 1, 1917, midnight</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>After a long talk with President yesterday in which I fully presented
                    Department’s views and hopes, as expressed in the Department’s January 26, 4
                    p.m., spoke of the general apprehension of public disorder at elections and
                    regretted that nothing had been said publicly by one in authority to reassure
                    the people, he assured me the Government’s measures were being taken only to
                    enforce order and insure safety to votes of both parties. Elections he declared
                    would be held according to law and the liberals were agitating the country with
                    contrary reports. As a probable result of this interview General Nunez, Vice
                    Presidential candidate, has published long, full statement assuring public there
                    need be no apprehension of lawlessness or misuse Government’s powers. This has
                    had a good effect. Liberal party council is tonight considering asking the
                    United States to supervise elections on the fourteenth.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gonzales</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
